	{noteno: 5, notetext: "The meaning is that an Emperor shall come, who shall restore the Church from its captivity, and reestablish the Divine order upon earth, in rise mutually dependent and severally independent authority of Church and Empire."},
	{noteno: 6, notetext: "This prophecy is too obscure to admit of a sure interpretation. Five hundred, ten, and five, in Roman numerals, give the letters D X V; which by transposition form the word Dux, a leader."},
	{noteno: 7, notetext: "The harlot, who had no right in the car, but had stolen her place there, or, in plain words, the Popes who by corruption had secured this papal throne."},
	{noteno: 8, notetext: "Obscure as the oracles of Thiemis or the enigmas of the Sphinx."},
	{noteno: 9, notetext: "According to a misreading of a verse in Ovid&rsquo;s <em>Metam.</em>, vii. 759, the Naiades solved the riddles of the oracles, at which Themis, offended, sent forth a wild beast to ravage the flocks and fields."},
	{noteno: 10, notetext: "Robs it as Adam did, splinters it as the Emperors did."},
	{noteno: 11, notetext: "A river of Tuscany, whose waters have a petrifying quality."},
	{noteno: 12, notetext: "Darkening thy mind as the blood of Pyramus dyed the mulberry."},
	{noteno: 13, notetext: "If not clearly inscribed, at least so imprinted on the mind, that, like the palm on the pilgrim&rsquo;s staff, it may be a sign of where thou hast been and of what thou hast seen."},
	{noteno: 14, notetext: "How far its doctrine is from my teaching."},
	{noteno: 15, notetext: "The having been obliged to drink of Lethe is the proof that thou hadst sin to he forgotten, and that thy will had turned thee to other things than me."},
	{noteno: 1, notetext: "Which shifts as seen from one place or another."},
	{noteno: 1, notetext: "Here for the first and only time is the beautiful Lady called by name."},
	{noteno: 2, notetext: "Eunoe, “the memory of good,” which its waters restore to the purified soul. The poetic conception of this fair stream is exclusively Dante&rsquo;s own."}
